reference_review:
POINTS:
- [src/test/benchmarks/io/vertx/benchmarks/FutureListenerBenchmark.java:36] this could allocate consume
- [src/test/benchmarks/io/vertx/benchmarks/FutureListenerBenchmark.java:28] Or you can add a field to the benchmark

```java
@State(Scope.Thread)
public class FutureListenerBenchmark extends BenchmarkBase implements Handler<AsyncResult<Void>> {

private int consumed;

public void handle(Void event) {
    consumed++;   
}
```
and return it on `addListeners()`:
```java
@Benchmark
  public int addListeners() throws Exception {
    Promise<Void> promise = Promise.promise();
    Future<Void> future = promise.future();
    consumed = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < listenerCount; i++) {
      future.onComplete(this);
    }
    promise.complete();
    return consumed;
  }
```
At this point, for clarity, you can define a separated per-thread `State` class to be passed to `addListeners` as argument; will make easier to understand that its a per-thread context (it will implements Handler too)

