reference_review:
POINTS:
- [core/spring-boot/src/test/java/org/springframework/boot/logging/LoggingSystemTests.java:78] This seems more complicated than necessary. I think a test like this would suffice:

```
@Test
void log4j2CanBeForcedUsingSystemProperty() {
	System.setProperty(LoggingSystem.SYSTEM_PROPERTY, Log4J2LoggingSystem.class.getName());
	assertThat(LoggingSystem.get(getClass().getClassLoader())).isInstanceOf(Log4J2LoggingSystem.class);
}
```

It would be good to also add a similar test for JUL.
- [core/spring-boot/src/main/java/org/springframework/boot/logging/log4j2/Log4J2LoggingSystem.java:134] Rather than overloading the constructor, I think we could go back to a single constructor that just accepts a `ClassLoader`. Something like this:

```java
Log4J2LoggingSystem(ClassLoader classLoader) {
	super(classLoader);
	org.apache.logging.log4j.spi.LoggerContext spiLoggerContext = LogManager.getContext(classLoader, false);
	Assert.isInstanceOf(LoggerContext.class, spiLoggerContext);
	this.loggerContext = (LoggerContext) spiLoggerContext;
}
```

The `Factory` inner class could then catch the `IllegalArgumentException` that may be thrown by the isInstanceOf assertion and continue, thereby allowing `null` to be returned as before.

